  "signature": "ed25519:7c3a1f9d2e6b4a8c0f5d3b7e1a4c9f2d6b0e8a3c7f1d5b9e2a6c0f4d8b2e7a1c5",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3 COU.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is a commercially validated finite element solver subject to ISO 9001 quality management. FDA internal verification procedures and DePuy Synthes solver qualification records confirm software versioning, regression testing, and change control. Achieved gradation 3 reflecting documented institutional QA protocols across all three modeling teams."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems must reproduce analytical solutions within 1% for representative load cases.",
      "rationale": "Patch test, single-element bending, and beam-bending benchmark cases were executed for each solver instance. All three modeling teams achieved residual errors below 0.5% against Timoshenko beam theory reference solutions. Code verification is documented in supplemental verification reports for each participating institution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change less than 2% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was performed on the non-cannulated screw geometry using three successive refinement levels (coarse, medium, fine). Construct stiffness and yield force QoIs changed by less than 1.3% between the medium and fine meshes, confirming discretization error is below the 2% threshold. Final mesh element count was approximately 180,000 second-order tetrahedral elements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge below 1e-6 for all load steps; nonlinear force residual norms below 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "All analyses used a direct sparse solver with double-precision arithmetic. Force and displacement residual norms were monitored at each nonlinear increment; maximum observed residual norm at convergence was 8.2e-7, satisfying the 1e-6 criterion. No solution divergence or spurious hourglass modes were detected across the 11-specimen ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent model review by a second analyst not involved in model construction; documented sign-off required.",
      "rationale": "Each of the three participating modeling teams performed an independent cross-check of boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application. Discrepancies identified during cross-review (primarily minor contact stiffness settings) were resolved prior to final simulation runs. Review sign-off records are archived in each institution's project documentation system."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model must capture elastic-plastic behavior of titanium alloy; contact formulation must represent screw-rod and rod-block interfaces.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model was applied to the Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod components, with material constants derived from coupon tensile testing reported in the study. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) was defined at all screw-rod and block-rod interfaces. The model form is consistent with established practice for metallic implant FEA under quasi-static loading as referenced in FDA guidance and prior ASME V&V 40 applications."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions must be traceable to measured specimen data; uncertainty bounds documented.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength for Ti-6Al-4V were taken from coupon measurements reported in Nagaraja et al. (2022). Screw geometry was derived from manufacturer-supplied CAD with dimensional verification against physical specimens. Input uncertainty was propagated using a Monte Carlo approach (n=1000 samples) confirming QoI sensitivity to material property variation is less than 3%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Minimum N=10 test specimens; specimens must be production-representative and lot-traceable.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were drawn from production lots and are representative of commercial devices. Lot traceability records were maintained and provided to FDA. Sample size exceeds the minimum required for statistical comparison using the E/uval metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the clinically relevant range of loading parameters; at least two distinct load configurations required.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 configuration (static compression-bending at standard offset). While this configuration is the regulatory standard, it does not cover the full range of in vivo loading scenarios (e.g., torsion, lateral bending). Achieved level is below required level; this shortfall is acknowledged and accepted given that F1717 is the predicate-consistent test method for 510(k) clearance and the model influence is rated Medium."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters must be demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions; boundary conditions must replicate fixture constraints.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry, grip dimensions, offset distance, and actuator displacement rate were replicated in the FEA boundary conditions based on ASTM F1717 fixture drawings and laboratory-supplied fixture measurements. Displacement-controlled loading in the model matches the experimental protocol. Equivalency was confirmed by comparing reaction force at the fixture reference point between simulation and experiment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval or percent difference) must be computed for all primary QoIs; acceptance bounds pre-specified.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. For each QoI, percent difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental measurement was less than 10%, and the E/uval metric was below 1.96 for all three quantities across all three modeling teams. Pre-specified acceptance bounds were documented in the analysis plan prior to unblinding of experimental results."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment was conducted to evaluate whether the selected quantities of interest — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are clinically and regulatorily meaningful for the non-cannulated pedicle screw COU. Stiffness characterizes the immediate load-sharing behavior of the construct, yield force identifies the onset of permanent deformation that would compromise spinal fixation integrity, and force at 40 mm displacement corresponds to the ASTM F1717 regulatory endpoint used in 510(k) submissions. Expert panel review involving biomechanical engineers and a spine surgeon confirmed that these three QoIs collectively represent the safety-relevant performance envelope for the intended surgical application. The qualitative assessment further considered whether surrogate or derived quantities (e.g., stress concentrations at the screw-rod junction) would provide additional discriminatory value; the panel concluded that the three primary QoIs are sufficient given the compression-bending loading mode and the medium model influence rating. No structured gradation scoring was applied to this factor, as the relevance determination is inherently judgment-based and the literature does not prescribe quantitative thresholds for QoI relevance in this device category.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must correspond to clinically and regulatorily recognized performance endpoints for spinal fixation implants under ASTM F1717 compression-bending."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must directly address the intended use scenario; experimental protocol must match the regulatory submission context.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity — ASTM F1717 static compression-bending bench testing of N=11 production constructs across two independent laboratories — directly corresponds to the regulatory submission context for a Class II pedicle screw system. The FEA model is applied to the identical geometry, loading mode, and boundary conditions as the physical test. The validation is therefore considered highly relevant to the COU, with no extrapolation required between the validation scenario and the intended regulatory use."
    }
  ],
